00:07:42.739 --> 00:07:49.420
can't remember his name exactly, but it's, his surname is Goldblatt, I think. And, and,

00:07:51.619 --> 00:07:59.299
and this, so yeah, it's talking about the theory of constraints and what its implication

00:07:59.299 --> 00:08:06.940
is for how you manage work and how you assign resources and how you, yeah, prioritize things

00:08:06.940 --> 00:08:12.019
basically. And why it's also interesting is because out of it, and out of all this, you

00:08:12.019 --> 00:08:16.980
know, this idea of visible work also emerges. So these things are all like quite tightly

00:08:16.980 --> 00:08:23.940
interwoven, right? And I've developed this, I had a bit of an epiphany while reading The

00:08:23.940 --> 00:08:29.260
Goal, which is, and I think I need to read both again to like really dig in. But I had

00:08:29.260 --> 00:08:35.299
a bit of an epiphany that I'm hoping others recognize or they've seen the solution to or

00:08:35.299 --> 00:08:39.140
people just like, oh yeah, you know, that is a thing. Or, you know, am I just being

00:08:39.179 --> 00:08:45.979
a bit crazier? So if you're not familiar with the theory of constraints, the very, very

00:08:45.979 --> 00:08:51.099
basics of it is, is that in any system of production, and that includes knowledge work,

00:08:51.900 --> 00:08:57.700
where the work is being handed off between people, or like in a manufacturing setting,

00:08:57.700 --> 00:09:02.900
you know, like your car parts need to go through some machine at some point, somewhere in this

00:09:02.940 --> 00:09:09.500
line of like the series of work events, one or more of the items or one or more of the

00:09:09.500 --> 00:09:15.539
work sensors, as they call it, is your bottleneck. Your bottleneck is your constraints. And you

00:09:15.539 --> 00:09:21.539
need to, you'll get optimum performance out of the whole system if you design around the

00:09:21.539 --> 00:09:27.580
constraints, like most people design around the full capacity of maximizing every single

00:09:27.580 --> 00:09:32.099
work sensors capacity. And that causes huge all sorts of issues. I'm not going to recount

00:09:32.099 --> 00:09:36.619
the whole book, but the idea is that you, you basically scale everything down and keep the

00:09:36.619 --> 00:09:44.299
constraints fully, let's say fully capacitated. And, and when I was reading it, I thought,

00:09:44.299 --> 00:09:47.859
okay, this is, yeah, it makes a lot of sense. And a lot of what they were saying, I

00:09:47.859 --> 00:09:52.859
recognize in my own kind of stuff I've learned in a reverse engineered kind of way, like,

00:09:52.859 --> 00:09:56.380
oh, yeah, you know, you don't want to maximize everyone's capacity and queues and

00:09:56.380 --> 00:09:59.900
workloads. And I thought, okay, this, so it was really like quite mind blowing, lots of

00:09:59.900 --> 00:10:06.619
those readings. But there's one thing that I know, here's my epiphany, that the idea is that

00:10:06.659 --> 00:10:12.140
your constraints needs to be able to keep pulling work as it's available. And that's the

00:10:12.140 --> 00:10:16.539
whole idea of having visible work, you keep pulling work as it's available. And that's work

00:10:16.539 --> 00:10:22.260
going through the constraints goes to other work sensors. If there's any delay at the

00:10:22.260 --> 00:10:27.739
constraints or any lowering of capacity at the constraints, the problem is that you keep

00:10:27.739 --> 00:10:32.580
building like each of those delays becomes cumulative. And that's why small delays,

00:10:32.580 --> 00:10:38.099
especially if your constraints somewhere near the front or on remember the exact positioning,

00:10:38.500 --> 00:10:43.419
but you get very large delays later on. And that's why you'll see I mean, you can see it

00:10:43.419 --> 00:10:48.020
when when people are working like small issues up front become someone else's massive

00:10:48.020 --> 00:10:52.340
nightmare down the chain, and they can just never catch up with work that was

00:10:52.380 --> 00:10:56.340
overwhelming, because they're dealing with all this upstream cumulative delays. And the

00:10:56.340 --> 00:11:04.179
cumulative delays is super important to be aware of. But now the solution, I think,

00:11:04.659 --> 00:11:13.219
doesn't quite work for much of data work that just in maximizing the capacity of your, of

00:11:13.219 --> 00:11:18.580
your bottleneck. And I think the reason is, now I'm not talking, okay, so most of my data

00:11:18.580 --> 00:11:23.020
work has been around, you could say, like, data analytical work, not productionizing,

00:11:23.700 --> 00:11:27.900
machine learning systems, I think productionizing that is more akin to the DevOps

00:11:27.900 --> 00:11:32.700
environment, like an IT, someone designing and developing something and then handing over to

00:11:32.700 --> 00:11:38.020
someone else to deploy. That's more like how everything else usually works. But in a lot of

00:11:38.020 --> 00:11:45.419
data work, that's very iterative. There's this huge problem in that most likely your

00:11:45.419 --> 00:11:55.739
bottleneck becomes a victim of its own delays. Right, because work often is not done, it's

00:11:55.739 --> 00:12:01.539
not just handed over, by necessity, you've got to hand over an analysis to someone. But

00:12:01.539 --> 00:12:06.979
that's not the end of it, we all know it comes back again. And a lot of the techniques that

00:12:07.419 --> 00:12:15.299
otherwise you might build in to reduce that rework. You know, in a software setting, you

